Worst piece of scripted crap I've ever played. I know - I have hundreds of hours into it.
If you care about wasting a few mins to read my comment and the exact reasons why it's shit be my guest.
Breakdown:
The game is not a football simulator. 
Especially in Ultimate Team mode (not sure if it applies to friendlies or every god damn match) the game tries to simulate "drama" - that means giving a player an advantage or disadvantage based on the current score.
Lets say you lead 1-0 and you are getting close to finishing the game. But oh no - the opponent breaks on the counter and your 90 rated CB and fullbacks suddenly feel like they gave up on life and need therapy. And your opponent equalises and maybe smashes another right after you lose the ball from kickoff.
You might say it's "random", blame the lag, blame the controller, blame your PC for not having a bazillion hertz processor. 
NO.
It's the game doing things on purpose.
And also it applies to matches in a row in FUT mode. Win a couple - then you absolutely must encounter a no lifer with 99 team that also gets an advantage (not his fault poor guy) because he may also come after a losing streak of 3-5 games. So the betting machine that is now EA must give him some juice or he quits the game and stops pouring shit tons of money on those cards.
PS: Bought the game on offer a year ago or so for 15 EUROs. Maybe you can have some fun in career mode - manager or player. Don't waste your money on packs and crap like that.
But be ready for the roulette because skill is only a small part of the game.
So 5/10 for me - that's me being generous because I actually played for so long.
And like any betting crap it causes addiction - keep that in mind if you're new, but I bet most players here are decades old addicts playing since 2010 or so.

EA FIFA 23 on Steam: A Nightmare of Logins, Launch Failures, and Customer Support Abyss"

I regret to say that my experience with EA FIFA 23 on Steam has been nothing short of a nightmare, and I feel compelled to share my frustrations to warn potential buyers. The game's demand for an EA login before you can even kick off a match is an unnecessary hassle, but that's just the tip of the iceberg.

The real problem surfaces when the game simply refuses to launch due to persistent issues with the EA app. It's a disheartening loop that renders your purchase useless, leaving you stuck with a game you can't play after shelling out your hard-earned money. But the true test of a gaming platform's worth lies in its customer support when issues arise, and both EA and Steam have left me thoroughly disappointed.

Attempting to seek assistance from Steam, where the purchase was made, proved to be an exercise in futility. Their support, or lack thereof, left me stranded, as they claimed an inability to support or refund even game bought directly from their store. On the other hand, when reaching out to EA, I was met with the same runaround, with the excuse that the game wasn't purchased through their platform, effectively absolving them of any responsibility.

This finger-pointing between Steam and EA is not only infuriating but indicative of a larger problem â€“ poor customer support on both fronts. It seems neither company is willing to take ownership of the issues surrounding their product. As a result, I find myself with a non-functional game and no recourse for a refund.

My advice to fellow gamers: steer clear of EA FIFA 23 on Steam, and I go further to suggest avoiding any EA-related titles on this platform altogether. The combination of login hassles, launch failures, and abysmal customer support creates an experience that is nothing short of a gaming nightmare. Save your money, your time, and your sanity by investing in titles from developers and platforms that prioritize the customer experience. EA FIFA 23 on Steam is a purchase you'll likely regret, and I urge all potential buyers to explore alternative options before being caught in the same frustrating cycle.

Of the news that will please some and some will knock their foreheads because of it, it should be mentioned that coach Ted Lasso and his team AFC Richmond have joined the game. Why is this a somewhat controversial addition? Of course, because both the coach and the club are completely fictional, made up for the hit Apple TV series.
Ted Lasso also appears in Ultimate Team, which, as usual, took the largest portion of innovation for itself. Because why bother with anything else when the online mode in which people spend real money on football player cards is making such profits?

The lovable, mustachioed American is certainly not the Ultimate Team's main draw. The change above the changes is a massive adjustment to the team play system, i.e. the rules according to which you can put together an effective eleven and then play with it against others. And again, it's a step that will suit someone, someone will stare at him incomprehensibly like Bobby Charlton at a red card.

Let's bounce back from the very basics: The new FIFA looks great again. If you sat my grandfather down in front of the TV, I'd bet you he wouldn't know the difference between a video game and an actual forball on TV for a precious moment. Everything works approximately as it should, no expense is spared on the visual processing of the players, nor the coaches, referees or spectators. It's next-gen.
The new episode also moves wonderfully. The players' movements are controlled by the second generation of HyperMotion technology, which already achieved good results last year and is even better this year. Football players are able to react smoothly to unpredictable events and ball bounces. The hand-to-hand fights look realistic, the goalkeepers' improvised interventions or unprecedentedly effective slides are perfectly processed.
A few solid improvements can't hide the fact that FIFA needs serious innovation.

FIFA 23, the last game with the famous name before the whole series is renamed EA Sports FC, is not as successful as the creators expected.
You can tell on and off the field that it is a new year, but unfortunately, this will tell you both some improvements and new, slightly incomprehensible failures. And over every slightly interesting idea that makes the Ultimate Team experience special, there hangs a shadow in the form of an almost unplayable career mode. [b] 85% [/b]

The disclaimer here is that I've only really played the individual career mode of the game - if that doesn't interest you or you'd like to dive into other modes, figuring out what they're worth prior, disregard this review.
That said, the career mode feels very untamed. You create a player that's supposed to be bad at the start, and are given a coach rating that determines, whether or not you're part of the main squad, a substitute or not even showing up to games. Then you simply get to pick a team to be drafted onto - weird, but an acceptable shortcut, I suppose.
You start training and soon realize that by simply training enough, the coach rating will go up enough to have you start a game. In said game, you're rather garbage, but can find your own positives. Still, unless you actively score/assist a bunch, the rating after each game goes down. So the loop is train -> rating up -> play -> rating down -> train. This also comes into play if you'd like to simulate any of the games on the schedule, as those simulations will obviously not count your input, but simply take your player's rating into account - a much faster degradation to the coach rating guaranteed.
The weird bit here is that, if you do play, regardless of your performance, your team will dominate every game. And I don't just mean win, I mean win by 5+ goals. Every time. I picked a good team, of course, but you almost don't need to do anything on the pitch. Doesn't matter the difficulty level either.
And so, you play, are rather unimpressive, get a ton of wins, train, take care not to simulate too often lest you'd like to train more, and don't really progress as a player in the meantime.

To whoever that plethora of words up there mattered, you're welcome. I realize I'm basing this off a single game mode, but I really prefer that game to everything else, primarily, and if it's such a lacklustre experience, I really don't care much for trying out the others.

FIFA 23 has once again raised the bar for soccer gaming, delivering a truly immersive and thrilling experience for fans of the beautiful game. EA Sports has meticulously crafted a title that not only maintains the high standards set by its predecessors but also introduces exciting new features that make it a must-play for any soccer enthusiast.

One of the standout features of FIFA 23 is the enhanced realism in player movement and ball physics. The fluidity of player animations, combined with the lifelike ball dynamics, creates an authentic and visually stunning representation of soccer. Every step, kick, and dribble feels incredibly responsive, making it easy to lose yourself in the virtual world of the sport.

The Career Mode has undergone significant improvements, offering a more immersive and strategic managerial experience. The addition of dynamic storylines and realistic transfer negotiations adds a layer of depth that keeps players engaged season after season. Whether you're guiding a team to domestic glory or managing your favorite club to international success, the Career Mode in FIFA 23 delivers a satisfying and rewarding journey.

Ultimate Team remains a highlight of the FIFA series, and FIFA 23 introduces exciting new features to keep the mode fresh and exciting. The addition of customizable stadiums, expanded player customization options, and innovative squad-building challenges add a strategic layer to the Ultimate Team experience. It's a mode that continues to evolve, providing endless opportunities for players to build their dream squads and compete against others worldwide.

The graphics and presentation in FIFA 23 are nothing short of breathtaking. Stadiums come to life with vibrant atmospheres, and player likenesses are remarkably detailed. The attention to detail, from the facial expressions of the players to the dynamic weather effects, contributes to an immersive and visually stunning gaming experience.

In terms of gameplay, FIFA 23 strikes an excellent balance between accessibility for casual players and depth for seasoned veterans. The controls feel intuitive, allowing newcomers to jump in and enjoy the action, while the advanced mechanics provide ample room for skillful play and strategic decision-making. The result is a game that caters to a broad audience, ensuring that everyone can find enjoyment regardless of their skill level.

Ok, so, I be fair. I have currently played 226 hours of this game and have no plans of stopping, but purely because itâ€™s the only non-manager focused soccer game out there. Itâ€™s not good, by any means. 
The gameplay is pretty standard, uninventive, and boring. I havenâ€™t played a fifa game consistently since World Cup 98, yet after a few seasons I was comfortable on legendary mode. The ai is pretty horrid which tanks most of the gameplay, otherwise it could be decent fun.
But here is the capstone to my â€œwould not recommendâ€ ratingâ€¦
Scripting.
Hot topic, I know, but just the same. After over 200 hours in the game I can say that anyone who doesnâ€™t believe scripting exists in this game is a complete buffoon.
Now, if EA admitted scripting was a part of the game then Iâ€™d be able to say I recommend this game and that I simply disagree with the decision to include that, but EA had even put their senior developers on the stand under oath to proclaim that scripting does not exist in any of their games. Meanwhile, I am playing a game with a score 17-3 and in the 90th minute the opposing team suddenly batters my defense and the game ends 17-9. Clearly didnâ€™t cause an issue for me but the fact that this scenario can even occur while the company claims they did not include scripting in the game is absolutely preposterous.
The real issue becomes there is no way to make the game consistently enjoyable. You either win games by a landslide, or you ALWAYS lose the random scripted game, usually a playoff or final. So you have the choice, play a boring ass difficulty? Or never win a cup.

"FIFA 23" feels like a missed opportunity for innovation in a long-standing franchise. While the core mechanics of soccer gameplay remain solid, the lack of substantial improvements or meaningful changes is disappointing.

The graphics, while generally polished, don't showcase a significant leap forward from previous iterations. The career mode, a staple of the series, suffers from a lack of innovation, with minimal improvements to player interactions and team management.

Microtransactions continue to be a sore point, impacting the game's balance and progression. The emphasis on Ultimate Team can overshadow other game modes, leaving those who prefer a more traditional soccer experience feeling neglected.

The commentary, despite efforts to inject realism, can become repetitive quickly, and the overall presentation lacks the freshness needed to truly captivate players.

"FIFA 23" may appeal to die-hard fans of the series, but for those expecting a notable evolution in gameplay and features, the experience may feel more like a roster update than a significant step forward.

I haven't bought FIFA since 2017 and I made FIFA 23 my first purchase in the franchise since my departure. It literally hasn't changed in the slightest on a mechanical level and the performance bugs I remember ARE STILL IN THE GAME! 

The most frustrating part are little visual hitches or menu glitches that I'm pretty sure could be fixed but for some reason haven't been. Whenever a player scores a goal and then runs to grab the ball from the net to take it back to the halfway line, the ball spins continuously in their hand for the cinematic...which may seem like a minor complaint but considering smaller indie games would fix a little blip in the animation/visuals like that within a month, the fact it's been left in the game THIS HUGE is so odd to me.

It's not horrendous, I mean it still works but it's basically the same game you've played a bazillion times and quite simply relies on your love of the game in order to keep buying it. EA simply do not care about the end result, because why not? it's the only football game out there that meets the requirements people want (i.e. their favourite teams, competitions etc.) and they go no further than that. Really depressing. Considering HOW BIG football has gotten, even more than it already was back when this football series began, it's insulting that they simply half ass this series when they make so much money from it.

There's definitely a lot good about FIFA 23, though the downfalls outnumber that by a long stretch. First of all, the game menus run really slow and has the occasional freeze or as EA puts it "error connecting to server", keep in mind this is a multi-billion dollar company. Second, the gameplay itself is completely unrealistic and has very little resemblance to the real world in terms of player awareness, skill, faults or errors, etc. Not to mention, the scripting of the game clearly favours one side. Online players can tell you all about that. Not worth the large price.

Here is my review on FIFA 23
If you play this game on pc or laptop it could be laggy depending on your device performance.
FIFA 23 FIFA WOMEN'S WOLD CUP 2023 - Manage your team to a World Cup trophy. This mode has alot of details in stats and teams. Overall I give this mode a 10/10
FIFA 23 LEAD YOUR COUNTRY - Play as a player or create your own player, this mode is fun as you lead your team to glory, Overall I give this mode a 10/10
FIFA 23 FIFA WORLD CUP 2022 - The main event in Football, the World Cup. This mode is well designed to give you that World Cup feeling. Overall I give this mode a 10/10
FIFA 23 VOLTA FOOTBALL - Play in the streets by yourself or with your friends, this mode has different ways to play, but the only issue is that no players are online, so you just have to play against a CPU. Overall I give this mode a 8.7/10 
FIFA 23 ULTIMATE TEAM - Make your ultimate team, this mode is brilliant but there are a few issues I have. Whenever I play online my controls change so I don't know how to play. This is very annoying as I can't play online because of this issue. Another issue I had was my team name not changing even after I changed it. Overall I give this mode a 6.9/10
FIFA 23 MANAGER CAREER - Sign, sell and loan players, this mode is so fun as you can sign any player you want. There is so much details in transfers and the cutscenes make you feel like a real manager. Overall I give this mode a 10/10
FIFA 23 PLAYER CAREER - Be a pro and win the Ballon d'Or, this mode has alot of details from teams trying to sign u, and managers unhappy or happy with your performance. Overall I give this mode a 10/10
This is my review on FIFA 23, the game can get laggy when playing on PC or computer, but the modes are brilliant so I give the game a 9.4/10

Holy hell. Even after 350 hours of gameplay of this 23 version, while having hundreds to thousands more since FIFA 10, and giving the benefit of the doubt every single time, this game feels worse and worse, underdelivering every single time.

The worst one? i was lowering my expectation of the game to just a basic football game, but holy shit. The scripting is so desperate, it's not even funny anymore.

From the previous notion of mine that error of passes came randomly, now the probability is not random and i can always expect pass errors 90% of the time in regards to simple, open, long pass.

Invisible walls everywhere. It's like everywhere i'd like to go, there's invisible walls everytime. Messi and Mainoo having a war with their own feet. For example, if i want to dribble to the left, the foot will fight every single time to mess it up. SIMPLE DRIBBLE!! FFS!

It's gotten to a desperation where mainoo got his ball possession ripped away from him, in the most blatant way possible. Simple dribble to the right, the game just swipes the ball a bit to the side, right in between the opps legs. Just like that, possession lost, counter, with my defenders bugged out of course, suddenly having invisible walls to just fucking sprint normally to the player, and boom. GOAL conceded. BASIC FUCKING FOOTBALL!! Apparently it's too much to ask!

I gave the game the benefit of the doubt, probably it's my PC that's too much of a potato. But having your players move in a slow motion just at the moment they got in front of an opps, it's too blatant to not call it a script. Purposefully undershoot or overshoot simple passes every single time? My players not getting the rebound and net it to the goal, but just stares at it instead?? C'mon, at least make it hard to notice, EA!!!

And i love how this game can never not deliver to script my players to come to awkward angles for everything. When it's just in time to do some pass, the foot will magically position itself, out of ordinary, to some weird awkward angles, and boom. Pass error. Same thing with shooting, the legs will automatically adjust to an awkward position, boom. Shot error, or easy ass shot. Same thing with dribbling. The body will adjust to some awkward position, boom. Handball.

It's too blatant of scripting, it's not even funny anymore. It's just too much of a sore to the eye, it may pinch my eyeballs out of its place

Oh, and suddenly the players went to ice skate in the middle of the field!! The best feature EA gave to this game! How many more times can you find football players went ice skating with their football cleats in the middle of the field??

FIFA 23: The King of Games Returns for Football Enthusiasts

[Introduction]

"FIFA 23" is a soccer simulation game developed and published by EA Sports. The FIFA series is one of the most popular and beloved franchises in the world of soccer gaming. FIFA 23 offers players the opportunity to control some of the best soccer teams worldwide and build their own soccer careers.

[Gameplay]

FIFA 23 delivers the highest level of soccer simulation. Players take control of real soccer stars, participate in matches, implement tactics, and develop strategies. The game offers realistic ball physics, player movements, and tactical depth.

The game features various modes, including the career mode where players can build their soccer careers as players or managers. Additionally, online multiplayer modes allow players to compete against soccer enthusiasts worldwide.

[Graphics and Sounds]

"FIFA 23" impresses with its visual and audio quality. Detailed player and stadium designs bring players closer to the atmosphere of real-world soccer. Player voiceovers and stadium sound effects enrich the match atmosphere even further.

[Conclusion]

"FIFA 23" is a must-have for soccer enthusiasts, offering a high-quality soccer simulation. With its realistic gameplay, stunning graphics, and atmospheric sounds, it immerses players into the world of soccer and elevates the excitement of the sport to the highest level. The FIFA series has traditionally been a pioneer in soccer gaming, and FIFA 23 continues this tradition.

Rating: 7/10

Now, at the end of the season when everyone has nearly identical top-tier lineups, it's more evident than ever how scripted this game is. In situations where both teams have a 99-rated goalkeeper, yours makes 0 saves out of 7 shots, while the opponent's identical goalkeeper makes 12 saves out of 14 shots. A 99-rated forward misses the goal in situations where a bronze player would easily score. The 45th minute is always dangerous, and so on. Basically, the essence of FIFA year after year is to either learn to play by the scripts or just enjoy those matches where FIFA has decided you will win.

FIFA 23 is easily THE worst football game I've ever played (and I grew up playing Nintendo Super Soccer on the SNES...).

After you manage to navigate the horribly optimised purgatory that is the menu, you'll soon find that many of the games essential mechanics are either broken or inconsistent. After choosing to overlook these frustrating shortcomings for the sake of enjoying a modern football title with friends, I also lost almost every Ultimate Team player I had accumulated and EA did basically nothing to resolve it. This is an issue faced by other players I know who also have had very little assistance from EA to resolve. It really is no wonder that EA have lost the FIFA licence with this being their final entry.

The strongest selling point of this game is the graphics and ball physics (when they work) which, admittedly are pretty impressive (most of the time), but it doesn't merit the hefty price tag this game demands from players on graphics and basic physics alone. With this being an EA title, I'm genuinely surprised I didn't have to use micro transactions to even have my players kick the ball...

All in all, a total waste of your time and money. DO. NOT. BUY.

Polish patties (kotlety)

Ingredients:
1 crusty white bread roll
120ml milk
1 onion, finely chopped
vegetable oil, for frying
500g beef mince
1 egg
1 garlic clove
pinch of marjoram
75g dried breadcrumbs

STEP 1
Soak the bread roll in the milk so it softens completely. Meanwhile, fry the onion in the oil for around 8 mins or until soft and golden. Add the fried onion to the beef mince along with the egg, garlic, marjoram and some seasoning. Squeeze the excess milk from the bread roll and add it to the mince mixture. Mix everything together and season well.

STEP 2
Divide the meat into 8 patties. Tip the dried breadcrumbs into a shallow bowl and coat the patties in it, all over. Heat some oil in a deep frying pan and fry the patties in batches on both sides until browned and cooked through, about 6-7 mins on each side.

First, The issues... This game was not made for desktop. It has a lot of bugs and UI issues when used on the desktop.  You will need to use a controller to play the game even when just on manager mode and not playing the matches and leaving them to sim.  The UI was not designed at all for desktop consideration and it shows.  leading to mouse not being able to click on certain actions or eventually the mouse cant be seen and you have to flick between desktop and game for mouse to appear again in game screen.  I wanted a game where i was a manager of a team only.  My kids already had the game on PS4, so we set out a challenge to see who can end up with the best team after a few seasons.  On the PS4 when you win the prem league your given the prize money from the win and added to the transfer budget.  So example the club provide 79mil as standard transfer budget and then add 150m of the 179m of the prem win prize money.  On the desktop version however after winning prem league twice in row, i have a board message that we have the prize money and that is it.  it never gets added to transfer budget.  Even when the profit and financial goals were met by 1000% in previous season.   So EA has it seems do not like those with desktops and wont provide a an equal game experience and trying to engineer customers to buy the PS4 version.

It forces you to use the EA app.  didnt know this.  so had lots of issues here.  when installing the game it deleted my origin app for other games!  it even told me on a pop up it did this.  I do not know why.  it them chose my sons EA account and not mine and i had no way of selecting which account to use!  so now when my son plays fifa on other desktop or other EA games it losses connection to the EA app. lack of quality planning and foresight from EA again.

I have to play the game in windowed mode and not full screen to reduce amount of bugs i experience. 

I bought messi for fun at 29 mil.  Usually my shirt sales are 13 mil.  In first game with messi and another new starter. under finances it said shirt sales that week were 35 mil and said due to messi and my other new guy.  these transaction messages under finance, stay as a a log of each week.  i can always find previous weeks.  looking back at the shirt sales to show my kids.  the one for messi showing 35m was now missing.  The game seems to have data leaks which ultimately effects your income-> budget-> transfer budget.   same as with missing prise money.

The UI lacks proper filtering of those you scouted.  You should have an area for all that were scouted, kept and recorded.  Stats over time should indicate if they need to be reassessed again due to growth.  then a better area for transfer shortlists.  But to have 3 categories to select.   Currently everyone you shortlist are in one area with rudimentary column sorter without option to not filter.  Filters are very much needed i this game when playing as a manager.  as well as advanced filters to see from transfer shortlist their potential and certain attributes that you as a manager would be interested in.   It has none of those basic elements that you would expect to find.  Making you reliant on external websites that can do this.

It appears EA didnt consult with actual club managers when creating the scenes and actions between club managers to purchase players and loans.  what they offer is too simple with a reduced feeling of the experience.  I feel they missed a trick here and this could have been more developed to instil a greater emphasis of experience.  Making it a bit more tense and nail biting.  However the likeness of each player when negotiating is very good.   However why do they have to all wear the same single suit!  Lack of quality thought here.

Escape button or circle on controller is used a great deal in game.  So i am very annoyed when pressing circle /escape it also wants be to come out of game and not save.  This must happen countless times in an hour.  coming out of the game should have been different keys/buttons.  Like i said the game UI was not really thought about for the desktop user.

Overall i enjoyed the game, but playing on career manager mode or on desktop,  seems like the game was rushed and unfinished.  Certainly much better options should exist out there for those who want a football manager game.

Launch problems can be solved in hard way and easy way.

HARD WAY:
When you received the security boot problem, you can reboot your PC and go to the motherboard settings/advanced and turn it on.
Then you will receive:
This software cannot be used at same time as the game. please make sure it's not running, or restart your pc.: security violation (262146)
If this error mentioned "Hypervisor", you have to go to the configuration of your PC and disable it, if the error was as long as mine without mentioing a program, then i have found no solution for it but don't worry, still it can be solved in the easy way.


*After finding a solutions i asked my self: how much EA did cared for the last FIFA game they released and after almost a year to have time to at least solve the launch problems. so suddently i found the easy way solution.

EASY WAY:
REFUND

PS: Besides that, thank you for stop supporting FIFA after they helped you building your name. now have fun rereleasing a same games with little polish (and some times worst) each year, this time with fc brand.

The refereeing is egregrious, the AI will get away with clear red card challenges all game long, most of the time not even getting a yellow for slide tackling your attacker as they go through, clearing your players out way after the ball has released, anything that when you do, you immediately receive a red card for. Even if you win the ball, you will still get a red for a challenge the computer sometimes won't even be called a foul for. It's also far more lenient in giving extra time past the given time for half and end of game, giving the computer FAR more of a chance to advance the ball and score than it ever gives the player. And the goalkeeping is continuing to get worse and worse alongside the refereeing, if your keeper is below 80 there's almost no difference in their ability to stop shots, they are all next to useless. Frequently when you have them rush the ball, they will just go in some random other direction instead, leaving the goal wide open.

I must define FIFA 23's gameplay as anti-football. This videogame is satire, it's an insult to the sport.

Defensive gameplay is horrible, second man press is almost useless, you try to tackle the opponent and the ball bounces straight back to them every time. Defense from both sides leave gaps open on purpose so that there's more goals in the matches, and even if you try to fill those spaces, your players will open up somewhere else.

Attacking is decent in comparison, but still lacking. The ally AI's positioning inside the box is absolute trash. Turning a cross into a goal is much harder than it should be. Running behind defenders is too easy, and pace is ridiculous. Animations are cool until they are sped up out of nowhere because the game needs them to be faster due to whatever happens with how the game is coded.

Don't buy this game nor EAFC 24. Spend your money on a real football and practice some tricks instead, it'll be more fun and healthier for your body and mind.

Where do I start? The game is very poorly optimized, and very lacking in graphics settings. There is no option to lock fps to anything other than 30 or 60 fps, no anti-aliasing or v-sync settings, and no ray-tracing options. This is a console port.

Cutscenes are choppy, there are frame drops everywhere, and odd graphics anomalies too. Like tearing during cutscenes, glitches, and ghosting. This shouldn't be happening on an RTX 3090 at 3440 x 1440 (and no, this doesn't happen in any other game, so its not the hardware).

Otherwise the game itself is decent. At least it's not another "legacy edition" version of the game on PC. But until they optimize it further and add more graphics settings, I cannot recommend it.

I loved playing this game and I will miss it when switching over to EA FC but I do wanna point out some of the bugs that were consistent while playing this game. Firstly one of the most annoying bugs is not being able to mute your friend in game when playing cross platform. I like this feature but I personally don't need to talk to my friend in the game when I'm already in a discord call with them. Secondly the game runs amazing on PC but when doing an online friendly on PS5 I legit wanna stop playing with the amount of lag that I'm having to indulge in. It ruins the game so much that I stopped playing the game on PS5. So all I'm asking is to please make the game a little more functional on the PS5 version because its weird to see the players just randomly speed up and slow down. Lastly, unlike its counterpart, the PC version of the game can't seem to run the goal scoring animations as well. There is one in particular that comes to mind and its like the most annoying to watch and I try to avoid the animation as much as possible. Whenever you score a goal the player tends to run toward the goal and grabs the ball but whenever they grab the ball the ball just starts spinning like crazy. I also wanna point out that some of the stadiums camera angles seem to bug out when scoring a goal. More specifically Anfield.

FIFA 23, the game that revealed my true talent: being hilariously bad at football! With each clumsy tackle and misguided pass, I unintentionally turned my team into a circus act. But hey, even my virtual opponents must have felt pity, as they scored own goals just to balance the scales of justice. This comically bad gameplay was only matched by the game's glitches, where players performed gymnastic stunts instead of scoring. FIFA 23 delivered laughs, though probably not as intended. Despite its flaws, it provided a slapstick experience that made me feel like a footballing legend...in a parallel universe, that is!

I've been buying FIFA on PC since 2010. I skipped the last couple of years because I was sick of the legacy bugs and being stuck on the last-gen version.

I decided to give this version a shot, and as usual EA just does not care about your experience at all. The same input problems that have existed since at least 2010 are still here. You are required to use a 3rd party app (DS4Windows, DSX, etc) to get a controller to work without double inputs. The mouse cursor constantly resets to the center of the screen, and when it does this, it effects your inputs. It feels like your players can barely move in any direction, as if the game is reading inputs from your mouse. You must move your mouse off the screen or onto a second monitor, which will fix it briefly until it happens again 3 minutes later. This bug has been in many FIFAs but this is probably the worst it's been. The mouse is constantly resetting itself and affecting gameplay. Playing online like this is just an exercise in frustration.

Here's a 12 page thread on the technical support forum that started last October. Some people in the thread are conflating the double input issue and the mouse cursor issue, but either way, this is a 12 page thread that EA has completely ignored. 

https://answers.ea.com/t5/Technical-Issues/Fifa-23-mouse-cursor-bug/td-p/11880168/highlight/false

They don't care. Stop giving them money.

While the actual gameplay itself is good, the rest of it is horribly optimised for PC. It can be a real chore to get it to work as EA and Steam don't seem to play nicely together, and even if they do the EA servers seem to be often down. My son has about 300 hours in game but less than half of that actually being able to play,  I've spent many many hours going through workarounds and troubleshooting just to get it to load. If he hadn't been such a football nut, I would of got a refund in the first few weeks. Problems unfortunately don't seem to stop there, there are a number of menus that once you get in, there seems to be no way out unless you control/alt/delete.  While I'm sure that for consoles this is great, this seems to be another example of a cash grab by EA, a very poor PC conversion with little to no effort made to optimise for a PC environment. Can't recommend to anyone unless you really like troubleshooting or not being able to play a game that you paid for.

I only recommend game for manager mode, nothing else. The game feels scripted beyond belief, and where it intends to create realistic scenarios, it just forces choppy game play. FUT is a money scam, and online play has no benefits. Manager mode is a bright spot due to its ease of use, and the creativity you get to explore with football tactics. 

ONLY buy FIFA titles if they're on mega sale.

If you can get the game to launch (big if), the tutorial doesn't do a good job of teaching you how to play (especially for someone who hasn't played FIFA games before). It essentially only teaches shoot and pass, but nothing really more than that. I got well into a season before I knew how to lob, finesse shoot, protect the ball, lead pass, etc. Not worth the money, ultimately.

Updated review after 50 hours: After replacing my SSD and reinstalling the game, FIFA no longer saves my progress on career mode. I had to start over from scratch and now no progress gets saved at all, causing me to start over every single time I launch the game. Absolutely infuriating and EA should be ashamed of themselves for launching such a trash game.

Update 2: Latest updates are causing the game to crash when scrolling in the main menu; just another in a long series of issues that make this game not worth a bucket of warm spit.

Talk about the definition of a mixed review.... I bought the game in the fall of '23 after the first patch or two had came out, still was VERY difficult to get it to initially launch on a brand new solid PC. After some Youtube and Google searches, it was sorted out. Even after that, I had to learn to have my xbox controller turned on ahead of launch and to be careful to not use the keyboard on start up, or else I couldn't get the game to recognize my controller after..

Setup issues aside, the game looks beautiful, the player movement is solid and its overall a very joyful experience. As a season ticket holder of a NWSL team, it would have been nice to have slightly more accurate women's player models. Still a great step forward to see the league represented. Hopefully next year's can have the actual stadium used for all the teams available.
